GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
Apr 30, 2026
SESSION 2025
HOUSE PRINCIPAL CLERK
H D
HOUSE BILL DRH40680-MGa-196
Short Title: Reorganize & Fund Rare Disease Adv. Council. (Public)
Sponsors: Representative Carney.
Referred to:
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT REVISING THE COMPOSITION AND DUTIES OF THE ADVISORY COUNCIL
3 ON RARE DISEASES; TRANSFERRING THE COUNCIL TO THE DEPARTMENT OF
4 HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES; AND APPROPRIATING FUNDS TO THE
5 DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES TO COVER THE OPERATING
6 EXPENSES OF THE COUNCIL.
7 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
8 SECTION 1. Part 6 of Article 1B of Chapter 130A of the General Statutes reads as
9 rewritten:
10 "Part 6. Taylor's Law Establishing the Advisory Council on Rare Diseases.
11 "§ 130A-33.65. Advisory Council on Rare Diseases; membership; terms; compensation;
12 meetings; quorum.
13 (a) Short Title. – This Part shall be known as Taylor's Law Establishing the Advisory
14 Council on Rare Diseases.
15 (a1) Establishment of Advisory Council. – There is established the Advisory Council on
16 Rare Diseases within the School of Medicine of the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill
17 Department of Health and Human Services to advise the Governor, the Secretary, and the General
18 Assembly on research, diagnosis, treatment, and education relating to rare diseases. This Part
19 shall be known as Taylor's Law Establishing the Advisory Council on Rare Diseases. For
20 purposes of this Part, "rare disease" has the same meaning as provided in 21 U.S.C. § 360bb.
21 (b) Advisory Council Membership. – The advisory council shall consist of 19 members
22 to be appointed as follows:
23 (1) Upon the recommendation of the Dean of the School of Medicine of the
24 University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, the The Secretary shall appoint
25 members to the advisory council as follows:the following 15 members:
26 a. A physician Two physicians licensed and practicing in this State with
27 experience researching, diagnosing, or treating rare diseases.
28 b. A medical researcher with experience conducting research concerning
29 rare diseases.
30 c. A One registered nurse or advanced practice registered nurse licensed
31 and practicing in the State with experience treating rare diseases.
32 d. One rare diseases survivor.
33 e. One member who represents a rare diseases foundation.
34 f. One representative researcher from each an academic research
35 institution in this State that receives any grant funding for rare diseases
36 research.
*DRH40680-MGa-196*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 g. One parent of a childhood rare disease survivor.
2 h. One hospital administrator, or the hospital administrator's designee,
3 representing a hospital in the State that provides care to persons
4 diagnosed with a rare disease.
5 i. Two persons age 18 or older who have been diagnosed with a rare
6 disease.
7 j. Two persons age 18 or older who are, or were previously, caregivers
8 to a person diagnosed with a rare disease.
9 k. One representative of a rare disease patient organization that operates
10 in the State.
11 l. One pharmacist licensed and practicing in this State with knowledge
12 and experience regarding drugs used to treat rare diseases.
13 m. One representative of the life sciences, biotechnology, or
14 biopharmaceutical industry that either focuses on research efforts
15 related to the development of therapeutic products for persons
16 diagnosed with a rare disease or has demonstratable understanding of
17 the path to commercialization of such products.
18 n. Two representatives of a health benefit plan or health insurer, at least
19 one of whom is a representative of a North Carolina Medicaid
20 Managed Care health plan.
21 o. One genetic counselor with experience providing services to persons
22 diagnosed with a rare disease or caregivers of persons diagnosed with
23 a rare disease.
24 (2) The chairs of the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Health and Human
25 Services, or the chairs' designees, shall serve on the advisory council. A
26 member of the advisory council who is designated by the chairs of the Joint
27 Legislative Oversight Committee on Health and Human Services may be a
28 member of the General Assembly.
29 (2a) One member appointed by the President Pro Tempore of the Senate.
30 (2b) One member appointed by the Speaker of the House of Representatives.
31 (2c) One member appointed by the Governor.
32 (3) The Secretary, or the Secretary's designee, shall serve as an ex officio,
33 nonvoting member of the advisory council.
34 (c) Members Length of Terms. – All initial members appointed pursuant to subsection
35 (b) of this section to the advisory council shall serve for a term of three years, and no member
36 initial member, except for the initial physician members and the initial member representing a
37 rare disease patient organization, shall serve more than three consecutive terms. The initial
38 physician members and the initial member representing a rare disease patient organization may
39 serve for up to four consecutive terms. Thereafter, members appointed by the President Pro
40 Tempore of the Senate, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, and the Governor shall
41 serve for a term of two years; and members appointed by the Secretary shall serve for a term of
42 two, three, or four years, as determined by the chair of the advisory council.
43 (c1) Vacancies and Removals. – Any appointment to fill a vacancy on the advisory council
44 created by the resignation, dismissal, death, or disability of a member shall be filled by the
45 appointing authority for the balance of the unexpired term. Each appointing authority may
46 remove any member appointed by that appointing authority for misfeasance, malfeasance, or
47 nonfeasance.
48 (d) Per Diem and Expenses. – Members of the advisory council shall receive per diem
49 and necessary travel and subsistence expenses in accordance with the provisions of G.S. 138-5
50 or G.S. 138-6 or travel and subsistence expenses in accordance with the provisions of
51 G.S. 120-3.1, as applicable.
